};

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the best form of B12 in gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Methylcobalamin is the preferred form because it is the bioactive coenzyme form of B12 that your body can use immediately without conversion. Cyanocobalamin, the synthetic form, must be converted to methylcobalamin through a two-step process involving the removal of cyanide and the addition of a methyl group. While both forms effectively raise serum B12 levels, methylcobalamin is retained in tissues longer and is particularly important for individuals with MTHFR gene variants who may have reduced conversion capacity. A 2015 study in Integrative Medicine found that methylcobalamin produced superior neurological outcomes compared to cyanocobalamin in patients with peripheral neuropathy.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much B12 do I need per day?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The Recommended Dietary Allowance for vitamin B12 is 2.4mcg per day for adults, 2.6mcg during pregnancy, and 2.8mcg during lactation. However, B12 gummies typically provide 500mcg to 3000mcg per serving because B12 absorption is inherently inefficient. The body absorbs only about 1.5mcg through the intrinsic factor pathway per meal, with an additional 1% of the remaining dose absorbed through passive diffusion. A 1000mcg supplement therefore delivers approximately 11.5mcg of absorbed B12, which comfortably exceeds the RDA.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can you take too much B12?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Vitamin B12 has no established Tolerable Upper Intake Level because it has an extremely low toxicity profile. Excess B12 is excreted through urine, and no adverse effects have been documented from high oral doses in clinical trials. The Institute of Medicine concluded that there is insufficient evidence to set an upper limit. However, very high serum B12 levels in the absence of supplementation can occasionally indicate liver disease or myeloproliferative disorders, so persistently elevated levels should be discussed with a healthcare provider.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Who is most at risk for B12 deficiency?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The groups at highest risk for B12 deficiency include vegans and vegetarians (B12 is found almost exclusively in animal products), adults over age 50 (reduced stomach acid impairs B12 absorption from food), individuals taking metformin for diabetes (metformin reduces B12 absorption by 10-30%), and people with gastrointestinal conditions such as Crohn disease, celiac disease, or those who have undergone bariatric surgery. The CDC estimates that approximately 6% of adults under 60 and nearly 20% of adults over 60 have inadequate B12 status in the United States.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do B12 gummies actually give you energy?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'B12 gummies can meaningfully improve energy levels if you have a B12 deficiency, because B12 is essential for red blood cell formation and cellular energy metabolism through the citric acid cycle. Correcting a deficiency often produces noticeable improvements in fatigue, mental clarity, and physical stamina within 2 to 4 weeks. However, if your B12 levels are already adequate, additional supplementation is unlikely to provide an energy boost beyond baseline. B12 is not a stimulant — it is a cofactor in metabolic processes that produce ATP.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between methylcobalamin and cyanocobalamin?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Methylcobalamin is the naturally occurring, bioactive form of B12 found in food and human tissues. It serves as a methyl donor in the conversion of homocysteine to methionine, a critical reaction for DNA synthesis and nervous system maintenance. Cyanocobalamin is a synthetic form that is more shelf-stable and less expensive to manufacture. It must be converted in the body by first removing the cyanide molecule and then attaching a methyl group. Both forms effectively raise blood B12 levels, but methylcobalamin demonstrates superior tissue retention and may be more effective for neurological applications.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When should I take B12 gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'B12 gummies are best taken in the morning or early afternoon because B12 plays a role in energy metabolism and circadian rhythm regulation. Some individuals report difficulty sleeping when taking B12 late in the evening, though this effect varies. Taking B12 with food is not strictly necessary for absorption, but it may reduce the mild nausea that some people experience with high-dose B12 on an empty stomach. Consistency is more important than timing — choose a time that fits your routine and take it daily.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are B12 gummies as effective as B12 injections?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'For most people with dietary B12 deficiency, high-dose oral B12 gummies (1000-2000mcg daily) are clinically equivalent to intramuscular injections. A landmark 2005 Cochrane review concluded that oral B12 supplementation at adequate doses was as effective as injections for correcting B12 deficiency and improving neurological symptoms. Injections bypass the digestive system entirely and remain necessary for patients with pernicious anemia (lack of intrinsic factor) or severe malabsorption conditions. For routine supplementation, gummies are a convenient and effective alternative.' },
    },
  ],
};
