    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h3>B12 Forms Compared: Absorption, Conversion, and Best Uses</h3>
      <p>The form of vitamin B12 in your gummy determines how efficiently your body can utilize it. Understanding the distinction between methylcobalamin and cyanocobalamin is the single most important factor in choosing a B12 supplement.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Methylcobalamin</strong>
          <p>The bioactive coenzyme form. Used directly by cells without metabolic conversion. Superior tissue retention and longer half-life. Preferred for neurological support and individuals with MTHFR variants. The gold standard for B12 supplementation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Cyanocobalamin</strong>
          <p>Synthetic form with excellent shelf stability. Requires two-step conversion: cyanide removal, then methylation. Well-studied and effective for raising serum B12 levels. Lower cost. Suitable for most healthy individuals without methylation concerns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Hydroxocobalamin</strong>
          <p>The form used in B12 injections. Longer retention time than cyanocobalamin. Rarely found in gummy format due to stability challenges. Excellent for clinical settings where sustained B12 levels are needed. Converts to both methyl and adenosyl forms.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Adenosylcobalamin</strong>
          <p>The mitochondrial coenzyme form. Critical for energy production in the citric acid cycle. Less commonly supplemented as standalone because methylcobalamin can be converted to adenosylcobalamin as needed. Emerging in premium B12 formulations.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Practical dosing guide:</strong> The RDA is only 2.4mcg, but B12 absorption is inherently limited. From a 1000mcg oral dose, you absorb approximately 10mcg (1.5mcg via intrinsic factor + ~8.5mcg via passive diffusion at 1%). For deficiency correction, 1000-2000mcg daily is the clinical standard. For maintenance, 500-1000mcg is sufficient for most adults.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
        <p><strong>Absorption declines with age:</strong> After age 50, up to 30% of adults develop atrophic gastritis, which reduces stomach acid production and impairs B12 liberation from food proteins. Supplemental B12 (in gummies or pills) is not affected by this condition because it is already in free form. The National Academies specifically recommend that adults over 50 obtain most of their B12 from supplements or fortified foods rather than relying solely on dietary sources.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

